-- PART 1: molecular-biology (48 easy, 48 medium, 49 hard)

('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the basic monomer unit of DNA?', 'Amino acid', 'Nucleotide', 'Monosaccharide', 'Fatty acid', 'B', 'DNA is a polymer made of nucleotide monomers, each consisting of a deoxyribose sugar, a phosphate group, and one of four nitrogenous bases.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'Which nitrogenous base is found in RNA but NOT in DNA?', 'Thymine', 'Adenine', 'Uracil', 'Guanine', 'C', 'RNA contains uracil instead of thymine. Uracil pairs with adenine just as thymine does, but lacks the methyl group present on thymine.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What type of bond holds complementary base pairs together in DNA?', 'Covalent bonds', 'Ionic bonds', 'Hydrogen bonds', 'Peptide bonds', 'C', 'Hydrogen bonds form between complementary bases — adenine pairs with thymine via two hydrogen bonds, and guanine pairs with cytosine via three hydrogen bonds.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'Which enzyme synthesizes new DNA strands during replication?', 'RNA polymerase', 'Ligase', 'DNA polymerase', 'Restriction endonuclease', 'C', 'DNA polymerase adds complementary deoxyribonucleotides to the 3'' end of a growing strand, synthesizing new DNA in the 5'' to 3'' direction.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the central dogma of molecular biology?', 'Protein → RNA → DNA', 'DNA → RNA → Protein', 'RNA → Protein → DNA', 'Protein → DNA → RNA', 'B', 'The central dogma states that genetic information flows from DNA to RNA via transcription, and from RNA to protein via translation.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'Which organelle is the site of translation in eukaryotic cells?', 'Nucleus', 'Mitochondria', 'Ribosome', 'Golgi apparatus', 'C', 'Ribosomes are the molecular machines that read mRNA and assemble amino acids into polypeptide chains during translation.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is a codon?', 'A sequence of three nucleotides on tRNA', 'A sequence of three nucleotides on mRNA that codes for an amino acid', 'A single nucleotide change in DNA', 'The binding site for RNA polymerase', 'B', 'A codon is a triplet of nucleotides on mRNA that specifies a particular amino acid or a start/stop signal during translation.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the anticodon?', 'A three-nucleotide sequence on mRNA', 'A three-nucleotide sequence on tRNA that is complementary to a codon', 'The promoter sequence on DNA', 'A stop signal in the ribosome', 'B', 'The anticodon on tRNA is complementary and antiparallel to the mRNA codon, allowing the correct amino acid to be delivered to the ribosome.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'Which strand of DNA serves as the template for transcription?', 'The coding strand', 'The template (antisense) strand', 'Both strands simultaneously', 'The lagging strand', 'B', 'RNA polymerase reads the template (antisense) strand in the 3'' to 5'' direction, synthesizing a complementary mRNA in the 5'' to 3'' direction.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is a gene?', 'Any segment of DNA in the genome', 'A segment of DNA that encodes a functional product such as a protein or RNA', 'A single chromosome', 'A protein that regulates cell division', 'B', 'A gene is a specific DNA sequence that encodes a functional product — most commonly a protein, but also functional RNA molecules like tRNA or rRNA.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'Which molecule carries the genetic code from the nucleus to the ribosome?', 'tRNA', 'rRNA', 'mRNA', 'snRNA', 'C', 'Messenger RNA (mRNA) is transcribed in the nucleus and travels to the cytoplasm, where it is read by ribosomes during translation.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the function of ligase in DNA replication?', 'Unwinds the DNA helix', 'Adds RNA primers', 'Joins Okazaki fragments together', 'Removes mismatched bases', 'C', 'DNA ligase seals the nicks between adjacent Okazaki fragments on the lagging strand by forming phosphodiester bonds, creating a continuous DNA strand.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is chromatin?', 'A type of lipid found in the nucleus', 'DNA wrapped around histone proteins', 'The fluid inside the nucleus', 'A collection of ribosomes', 'B', 'Chromatin is the complex of DNA and histone proteins that makes up chromosomes; it allows very long DNA molecules to be packaged compactly in the nucleus.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What does RNA polymerase do?', 'Replicates DNA', 'Joins DNA fragments', 'Synthesizes RNA from a DNA template', 'Translates mRNA into protein', 'C', 'RNA polymerase binds to the promoter region and synthesizes an RNA strand complementary to the DNA template strand, a process called transcription.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'Which of the following is a pyrimidine base?', 'Adenine', 'Guanine', 'Cytosine', 'Both A and B', 'C', 'Pyrimidines are single-ring bases; cytosine, thymine, and uracil are pyrimidines. Adenine and guanine are double-ring purines.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the structure of DNA described as?', 'Single-stranded linear molecule', 'Double-stranded alpha helix', 'Double-stranded antiparallel helix', 'Circular double-stranded molecule', 'C', 'DNA is a double helix in which two antiparallel strands (one running 5'' to 3'', the other 3'' to 5'') are held together by hydrogen bonds between complementary bases.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is a mutation?', 'Normal DNA replication', 'A change in the nucleotide sequence of DNA', 'The process of gene expression', 'Chromosome separation during meiosis', 'B', 'A mutation is a heritable change in the DNA sequence; it can affect a single nucleotide (point mutation) or involve larger chromosomal rearrangements.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'Which of the following correctly describes the 5'' to 3'' directionality of DNA synthesis?', 'New nucleotides are added to the 5'' phosphate end', 'New nucleotides are added to the 3'' hydroxyl end', 'Synthesis proceeds in both directions simultaneously on the same strand', 'The template is read 5'' to 3''', 'B', 'DNA polymerase can only add nucleotides to a free 3''-OH group, so synthesis always proceeds in the 5'' to 3'' direction on the new strand.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the start codon in eukaryotic translation?', 'UAG', 'UAA', 'AUG', 'UGA', 'C', 'AUG codes for methionine and serves as the universal start codon, signaling the ribosome to begin translation.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What are Okazaki fragments?', 'Short RNA sequences used as primers', 'Short DNA fragments synthesized discontinuously on the lagging strand', 'Pieces of mRNA produced by alternative splicing', 'Histone-free regions of chromosomes', 'B', 'Because DNA polymerase can only synthesize 5'' to 3'', the lagging strand is made in short discontinuous segments called Okazaki fragments that are later joined by ligase.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is translation?', 'The synthesis of RNA from DNA', 'The synthesis of a polypeptide from an mRNA template', 'The movement of tRNA from nucleus to cytoplasm', 'The replication of DNA before cell division', 'B', 'Translation is the process by which ribosomes decode the mRNA sequence and synthesize a corresponding polypeptide chain using amino acids delivered by tRNA.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'In DNA, if one strand reads 5''-ATCG-3'', what is the complementary strand?', '5''-TAGC-3''', '3''-TAGC-5''', '5''-CGAT-3''', '3''-GCTA-5''', 'B', 'The complementary strand is antiparallel and follows Watson-Crick base pairing: A pairs with T and G pairs with C, running in the opposite (3'' to 5'') direction.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is a promoter?', 'A protein that breaks down DNA', 'A DNA sequence where RNA polymerase binds to initiate transcription', 'A ribosomal binding site on mRNA', 'An enzyme that activates translation', 'B', 'The promoter is a regulatory DNA sequence upstream of a gene where RNA polymerase (with transcription factors) binds to begin transcription.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'Which base pairing rule states that adenine pairs with thymine in DNA?', 'Griffith''s principle', 'Chargaff''s rules', 'Mendel''s laws', 'The wobble hypothesis', 'B', 'Chargaff''s rules state that in DNA, [A] = [T] and [G] = [C], reflecting the specific hydrogen bonding between complementary base pairs.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the role of primase during DNA replication?', 'It joins Okazaki fragments', 'It synthesizes short RNA primers to initiate synthesis', 'It proofreads newly synthesized DNA', 'It unwinds the DNA helix', 'B', 'Primase synthesizes a short RNA primer complementary to the template strand, providing the 3''-OH group that DNA polymerase needs to begin adding deoxyribonucleotides.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'Which of the following is a post-transcriptional modification of eukaryotic pre-mRNA?', 'Addition of histones', 'Splicing out of introns', 'Methylation of cytosine bases', 'Phosphorylation of RNA polymerase', 'B', 'Eukaryotic pre-mRNA undergoes splicing to remove introns (non-coding sequences), as well as 5'' capping and 3'' polyadenylation, before it is exported as mature mRNA.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What are introns?', 'Protein-coding sequences in mRNA', 'Non-coding sequences in a gene that are removed during RNA processing', 'Short regulatory RNA molecules', 'DNA sequences that encode rRNA', 'B', 'Introns are intervening sequences within a gene that are transcribed into pre-mRNA but spliced out before the mature mRNA is translated.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What are exons?', 'Sequences removed during RNA splicing', 'Non-coding spacer sequences in DNA', 'Coding sequences that remain in mature mRNA', 'Repetitive sequences at chromosome ends', 'C', 'Exons are the expressed sequences of a gene; after splicing removes introns, the exons are joined together in the mature mRNA that is translated into protein.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What does the poly-A tail on eukaryotic mRNA do?', 'Serves as the start codon', 'Protects mRNA from degradation and aids export from the nucleus', 'Codes for a string of lysine residues', 'Initiates ribosome binding at the 5'' end', 'B', 'The poly-A tail (a string of ~150–250 adenine nucleotides added to the 3'' end) protects mRNA from enzymatic degradation and assists in nuclear export and translation initiation.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the 5'' cap on eukaryotic mRNA?', 'A sequence of stop codons', 'A modified guanine nucleotide added to the 5'' end', 'A poly-adenine sequence', 'A ribosome attachment site at the 3'' end', 'B', 'The 5'' cap is a methylated guanosine nucleotide that protects the mRNA from degradation and is recognized by ribosomes to initiate translation.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'Which ribosomal site holds the tRNA carrying the growing polypeptide chain?', 'A site', 'P site', 'E site', 'Initiation site', 'B', 'The P (peptidyl) site holds the tRNA attached to the growing polypeptide. The A site accepts the incoming aminoacyl-tRNA, and the E site is where the uncharged tRNA exits.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What type of RNA makes up the core structure of ribosomes?', 'mRNA', 'tRNA', 'rRNA', 'snRNA', 'C', 'Ribosomal RNA (rRNA) combines with ribosomal proteins to form the large and small subunits of the ribosome, and participates directly in catalyzing peptide bond formation.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is semiconservative replication?', 'Each new DNA molecule contains two entirely new strands', 'Each new DNA molecule contains one original strand and one new strand', 'DNA is replicated only in one direction', 'Only half the genome is replicated each cell cycle', 'B', 'In semiconservative replication, the two parental strands separate and each serves as a template for a new complementary strand, so each daughter DNA molecule contains one old and one new strand.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What experiment proved that DNA replication is semiconservative?', 'Griffith''s transformation experiment', 'Hershey-Chase experiment', 'Meselson-Stahl experiment', 'Avery-MacLeod-McCarty experiment', 'C', 'Meselson and Stahl used heavy (¹⁵N) and light (¹⁴N) isotopes of nitrogen to label DNA and showed that after one round of replication, all DNA molecules were hybrid (one heavy, one light strand).'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'Which of the following is the correct order of events in protein synthesis?', 'Translation → Transcription → mRNA processing', 'Transcription → mRNA processing → Translation', 'DNA replication → Translation → Transcription', 'mRNA processing → Transcription → Translation', 'B', 'In eukaryotes, DNA is first transcribed into pre-mRNA (transcription), which is processed into mature mRNA, and then the mRNA is translated into protein at the ribosome.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is a polypeptide?', 'A chain of nucleotides', 'A chain of amino acids linked by peptide bonds', 'A double-stranded RNA molecule', 'A type of lipid polymer', 'B', 'A polypeptide is a polymer of amino acids connected by peptide bonds formed between the amino group of one amino acid and the carboxyl group of the next during translation.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What type of mutation inserts or deletes one nucleotide, disrupting the reading frame?', 'Missense mutation', 'Nonsense mutation', 'Frameshift mutation', 'Silent mutation', 'C', 'A frameshift mutation shifts the reading frame of all codons downstream of the insertion or deletion, usually drastically altering the amino acid sequence and producing a nonfunctional protein.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'Which enzyme removes RNA primers and fills in the gap with DNA during replication?', 'Primase', 'Helicase', 'DNA polymerase I (in prokaryotes)', 'Topoisomerase', 'C', 'In prokaryotes, DNA polymerase I has 5'' to 3'' exonuclease activity to remove RNA primers and simultaneously replaces them with DNA nucleotides.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the function of topoisomerase during DNA replication?', 'Joins Okazaki fragments', 'Adds nucleotides to the growing strand', 'Relieves torsional strain ahead of the replication fork', 'Synthesizes RNA primers', 'C', 'As helicase unwinds DNA, positive supercoils accumulate ahead of the replication fork. Topoisomerase cuts and rejoins the DNA backbone to relieve this torsional stress.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'Which of the following correctly pairs a codon with its amino acid category?', 'UAA — codes for leucine', 'AUG — start/methionine', 'UGA — codes for tryptophan', 'UAG — codes for serine', 'B', 'AUG is the universal start codon that codes for methionine. UAA, UAG, and UGA are the three stop codons that terminate translation.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the term for the sequence of amino acids in a protein?', 'Tertiary structure', 'Secondary structure', 'Primary structure', 'Quaternary structure', 'C', 'The primary structure of a protein is the linear sequence of amino acids, which is determined directly by the mRNA codons read during translation.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What are telomeres?', 'Centromere proteins that attach to spindle fibers', 'Repetitive DNA sequences at the ends of chromosomes', 'Origins of replication on chromosomes', 'Non-coding sequences within genes', 'B', 'Telomeres are repetitive non-coding sequences (e.g., TTAGGG in humans) that cap chromosome ends, protecting them from degradation and preventing chromosomal fusion.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'Which of the following is a silent mutation?', 'A mutation that introduces a stop codon', 'A mutation that changes one amino acid to another', 'A mutation that changes a codon but not the amino acid it encodes', 'A mutation that shifts the reading frame', 'C', 'Because the genetic code is degenerate (multiple codons can encode the same amino acid), some nucleotide changes do not alter the amino acid sequence — these are silent (synonymous) mutations.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the function of single-strand binding proteins (SSBPs) during replication?', 'They synthesize RNA primers', 'They stabilize the separated DNA strands so they do not re-anneal', 'They join Okazaki fragments', 'They methylate newly synthesized DNA', 'B', 'SSBPs coat the single-stranded DNA template strands after helicase unwinds them, preventing the strands from re-pairing and keeping them available for DNA polymerase.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What does it mean that the genetic code is degenerate?', 'Many codons code for the same amino acid', 'Each amino acid is encoded by only one codon', 'All codons are stop signals', 'The code changes between species', 'A', 'The genetic code is degenerate (redundant) because most amino acids are encoded by more than one codon, especially differing in the third (wobble) position.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'Which of the following best describes epigenetics?', 'Changes in DNA sequence that alter gene function', 'Changes in gene expression without altering the underlying DNA sequence', 'Mutations caused by environmental radiation', 'The study of gene frequency in populations', 'B', 'Epigenetics refers to heritable changes in gene expression that do not involve changes to the DNA sequence itself, such as DNA methylation and histone modification.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the role of the spliceosome?', 'It methylates DNA at CpG islands', 'It adds the poly-A tail to pre-mRNA', 'It removes introns from pre-mRNA', 'It exports mRNA from the nucleus', 'C', 'The spliceosome is a large ribonucleoprotein complex made of snRNPs that recognizes splice sites on pre-mRNA and catalyzes the removal of introns and ligation of exons.'),

-- medium molecular-biology
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'A researcher finds that a bacterium has a G+C content of 40%. What percentage of its bases are adenine?', '40%', '20%', '30%', '10%', 'C', 'By Chargaff''s rules, G = C = 20% each (since G+C = 40%), so A + T = 60%, meaning A = T = 30% each.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'Which of the following would result from a missense mutation in the active site of an enzyme?', 'The enzyme sequence is unchanged', 'The enzyme may lose its catalytic activity', 'The reading frame is disrupted', 'Transcription terminates prematurely', 'B', 'A missense mutation changes one amino acid to another; if this occurs at the active site, the new residue may alter the shape or chemistry of the active site, reducing or eliminating catalytic function.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the significance of multiple origins of replication in eukaryotes?', 'It allows replication to proceed without primers', 'It enables the much larger eukaryotic genome to be replicated in a reasonable time', 'It prevents frameshift mutations', 'It allows each chromosome to be replicated by a different enzyme', 'B', 'Eukaryotic chromosomes are very large, so having thousands of origins of replication that fire simultaneously greatly reduces the time needed to replicate the entire genome.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'During translation, which event occurs at the A site of the ribosome?', 'The uncharged tRNA exits the ribosome', 'The growing polypeptide is transferred to the incoming aminoacyl-tRNA', 'The incoming aminoacyl-tRNA with its amino acid binds to the mRNA codon', 'The ribosome slides to the next codon', 'C', 'The A (aminoacyl) site accepts the incoming aminoacyl-tRNA whose anticodon matches the mRNA codon; the peptide bond is then formed transferring the polypeptide from the P-site tRNA to the A-site tRNA.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'A gene has an intron with a splice-site mutation. What is the most likely consequence?', 'The protein has one extra amino acid', 'The intron is retained in the mature mRNA, likely disrupting the protein', 'The protein folds incorrectly due to wrong disulfide bonds', 'Transcription of the gene is prevented', 'B', 'Splice-site mutations disrupt the consensus sequences (GU...AG) recognized by the spliceosome, preventing proper intron removal and resulting in intron retention or exon skipping, which typically disrupts the open reading frame.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'How does DNA methylation typically affect gene expression?', 'It increases transcription by opening chromatin', 'It stabilizes mRNA in the cytoplasm', 'It generally silences gene expression by condensing chromatin', 'It promotes ribosome binding to mRNA', 'C', 'Methylation of cytosine residues, especially at CpG islands in promoters, is associated with transcriptional silencing by recruiting proteins that compact chromatin into a less accessible heterochromatin state.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'Which of the following correctly explains why the lagging strand is synthesized discontinuously?', 'The lagging strand template contains more guanine residues', 'DNA polymerase can only extend in the 5'' to 3'' direction, which is away from the fork on this template', 'Helicase unwinds the lagging strand more slowly', 'The lagging strand lacks a promoter sequence', 'B', 'Because DNA synthesis must proceed 5'' to 3'', and the lagging strand template runs in the same direction as fork movement (3'' to 5''), synthesis must wait for more template to be exposed, occurring in short discontinuous fragments.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'What would happen if a cell lacked functional DNA polymerase proofreading activity?', 'DNA replication would stop entirely', 'Transcription rates would increase', 'The mutation rate during replication would increase significantly', 'Okazaki fragments would not be joined', 'C', 'The 3'' to 5'' exonuclease proofreading activity of DNA polymerase removes incorrectly incorporated bases; without it, replication errors would not be corrected, dramatically increasing the overall mutation rate.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'A protein has the sequence …Ala-Ser-STOP instead of …Ala-Ser-Gly-Lys. What type of mutation caused this?', 'Frameshift insertion', 'Missense mutation', 'Nonsense mutation', 'Silent mutation', 'C', 'A nonsense mutation changes a sense codon to a stop codon (UAA, UAG, or UGA), causing premature termination of translation and a truncated protein.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'Which statement about histone acetylation is correct?', 'It increases DNA methylation levels', 'It compacts chromatin and inhibits transcription', 'It relaxes chromatin structure, promoting transcription', 'It directly adds nucleotides to mRNA', 'C', 'Acetylation of lysine residues on histone tails neutralizes their positive charge, reducing their affinity for negatively charged DNA and loosening chromatin structure, making genes more accessible for transcription.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'Why does RNA polymerase not require a primer, while DNA polymerase does?', 'RNA polymerase is more accurate than DNA polymerase', 'RNA polymerase can initiate a new strand de novo by adding the first nucleotide without a pre-existing 3''-OH', 'RNA polymerase uses a different set of nucleotides', 'DNA polymerase requires higher temperatures to function', 'B', 'RNA polymerase can start a new RNA chain from scratch by adding the first ribonucleotide, whereas DNA polymerase can only add to an existing 3''-OH end, requiring a short RNA primer synthesized by primase.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'In eukaryotes, what is the first event in the elongation stage of transcription?', 'RNA polymerase dissociates from the DNA', 'RNA polymerase moves downstream, adding ribonucleotides complementary to the template strand', 'The pre-mRNA is immediately processed', 'Sigma factor is released from the complex', 'B', 'During elongation, RNA polymerase translocates along the template strand in the 3'' to 5'' direction, synthesizing the mRNA transcript by adding complementary ribonucleotides in the 5'' to 3'' direction.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'Which of the following describes a trans-acting regulatory element?', 'A DNA sequence adjacent to the gene it regulates', 'A protein or RNA that diffuses through the nucleus to regulate gene expression', 'A promoter sequence recognized by RNA polymerase', 'An intron within the regulated gene', 'B', 'Trans-acting factors (such as transcription factor proteins) are encoded at one location in the genome but act on target sequences (cis-elements) elsewhere, often on different chromosomes.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the molecular basis of the lac operon being inducible?', 'cAMP activates the promoter constitutively', 'Allolactose binds the repressor, causing a conformational change that releases it from the operator', 'Lactose methylates the operator, blocking repressor binding', 'The sigma factor is replaced by a lactose-specific factor', 'B', 'In the absence of lactose, the lac repressor binds the operator and blocks transcription. When allolactose (a lactose isomer) binds the repressor, it changes shape and can no longer bind the operator, allowing transcription.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'A protein-coding gene is 1,500 bp long (including introns). The mature mRNA is 900 nucleotides of coding sequence. Approximately how many amino acids does the protein contain?', '900', '500', '300', '150', 'C', 'Each codon is 3 nucleotides; 900 coding nucleotides ÷ 3 = 300 codons, which encode approximately 300 amino acids (minus the stop codon means ~299, but 300 is the best approximation here).'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the wobble position in a codon?', 'The first nucleotide of a codon', 'The second nucleotide of a codon', 'The third nucleotide of a codon', 'The nucleotide before the start codon', 'C', 'The wobble position is the third (3'') nucleotide of a codon; non-standard base pairing here allows a single tRNA to recognize multiple codons differing at that position, explaining the degeneracy of the genetic code.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'How do enhancers regulate transcription?', 'They are located within the coding sequence of the gene', 'They encode activator proteins that bind promoters', 'They are distant DNA sequences that, when bound by activators, loop to the promoter and increase transcription', 'They bind RNA polymerase directly and carry it to the promoter', 'C', 'Enhancers are cis-regulatory sequences that can be thousands of base pairs from the promoter; when activator proteins bind them, DNA looping brings the enhancer-bound complex into contact with the transcription machinery at the promoter.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'CRISPR-Cas9 is a genome-editing tool. What does Cas9 do?', 'Synthesizes new DNA at the cut site', 'Acts as an RNA polymerase', 'Cuts both strands of DNA at a site specified by a guide RNA', 'Ligates DNA fragments', 'C', 'Cas9 is an endonuclease that creates a double-strand break in DNA at the location complementary to the guide RNA sequence (adjacent to a PAM sequence), allowing targeted genome editing.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the purpose of gel electrophoresis in molecular biology?', 'To amplify specific DNA sequences', 'To separate DNA, RNA, or protein fragments by size', 'To sequence an unknown DNA fragment', 'To insert foreign DNA into a plasmid', 'B', 'Gel electrophoresis uses an electric field to move charged molecules through a gel matrix; smaller fragments migrate farther than larger ones, separating molecules by size.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'During mRNA translation, what triggers release of the polypeptide from the ribosome?', 'The ribosome runs out of aminoacyl-tRNAs', 'A release factor recognizes the stop codon in the A site', 'The poly-A tail is reached', 'The 5'' cap is removed', 'B', 'When a stop codon (UAA, UAG, or UGA) enters the A site, a release factor mimics tRNA and binds, stimulating hydrolysis of the polypeptide from the P-site tRNA, releasing the finished protein.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'Which of the following best explains why mutations in the TATA box reduce transcription?', 'The TATA box encodes a key amino acid in RNA polymerase', 'TFIID cannot bind the TATA box, preventing assembly of the preinitiation complex', 'The ribosome cannot bind the mRNA without a TATA box', 'The mutation shifts the reading frame of the coding sequence', 'B', 'TFIID (containing TBP) binds the TATA box in the core promoter; without proper TATA box sequence, TFIID binding is disrupted, preventing assembly of the full transcription preinitiation complex and dramatically reducing transcription.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'What distinguishes euchromatin from heterochromatin?', 'Euchromatin contains no histones', 'Euchromatin is loosely packed and transcriptionally active; heterochromatin is tightly packed and mostly silent', 'Heterochromatin is found only in prokaryotes', 'Euchromatin is replicated in late S phase', 'B', 'Euchromatin is in an open conformation accessible to transcription factors, while heterochromatin is compacted and generally inaccessible, silencing the genes within it.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'What is a restriction enzyme, and why is it useful in molecular cloning?', 'An enzyme that methylates DNA at specific sequences, used to silence genes', 'An enzyme that cuts DNA at specific recognition sequences, creating fragments for cloning', 'A protein that prevents foreign DNA from entering a cell', 'An enzyme that joins DNA fragments at any sequence', 'B', 'Restriction endonucleases cut double-stranded DNA at specific palindromic recognition sequences, generating defined fragments that can be ligated into vectors for cloning.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'What is PCR used for?', 'Separating DNA fragments by size', 'Sequencing an entire genome in one reaction', 'Amplifying a specific DNA sequence exponentially using repeated thermal cycles', 'Inserting a gene into a host organism', 'C', 'PCR (polymerase chain reaction) uses heat-stable DNA polymerase, primers, and repeated denaturation/annealing/extension cycles to exponentially amplify a target DNA region.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'How does siRNA (small interfering RNA) regulate gene expression?', 'It activates the promoter of target genes', 'It guides a protein complex (RISC) to degrade complementary mRNA', 'It methylates target gene promoters', 'It blocks the ribosomal A site', 'B', 'siRNA associates with the RISC complex; the siRNA strand guides RISC to complementary mRNA sequences, which are then cleaved and degraded, preventing translation of the target gene.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the significance of the Hershey-Chase experiment?', 'It showed that proteins are the transforming principle', 'It demonstrated that DNA, not protein, is the genetic material', 'It revealed the semiconservative nature of DNA replication', 'It proved that the genetic code is triplet', 'B', 'Hershey and Chase used radioactive labels (³²P for DNA, ³⁵S for protein) in bacteriophage infections and showed that DNA enters bacteria while protein stays outside, proving DNA is the genetic material.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'Which feature distinguishes mRNA from other RNA types in eukaryotes?', 'It contains the anticodon loop', 'It is the most abundant RNA in the cell', 'It carries the codons that specify a protein''s amino acid sequence', 'It forms part of the ribosome structure', 'C', 'mRNA is unique in carrying the protein-coding message as a sequence of codons; rRNA is the most abundant, tRNA carries amino acids, and only mRNA is translated into protein.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the role of the Shine-Dalgarno sequence in prokaryotic translation?', 'It marks the 3'' end of the mRNA', 'It is a ribosome-binding sequence upstream of the start codon on prokaryotic mRNA', 'It encodes the signal peptide for secretion', 'It is a consensus sequence found in all promoters', 'B', 'The Shine-Dalgarno sequence is complementary to the 16S rRNA of the small ribosomal subunit, positioning the ribosome near the AUG start codon for efficient initiation of translation in prokaryotes.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'Why is fidelity of DNA replication critical for multicellular organisms?', 'Low fidelity produces more genetic diversity, which is beneficial', 'Mutations in somatic cells can lead to cancer, making high replication fidelity essential', 'DNA replication errors correct themselves automatically', 'Fidelity matters only for germ cells', 'B', 'Errors during DNA replication in somatic cells can disrupt tumor suppressor genes or proto-oncogenes, potentially initiating cancer; multiple proofreading and repair mechanisms exist to keep mutation rates extremely low.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'What event initiates the elongation phase of translation?', 'The large subunit joins the initiation complex and the first peptide bond is formed', 'The stop codon enters the A site', 'The mRNA is exported from the nucleus', 'The poly-A tail is synthesized', 'A', 'After initiation (assembly of the ribosome at the start codon with the initiator Met-tRNA in the P site), the large subunit joins and the first aminoacyl-tRNA enters the A site, allowing peptide bond formation to begin elongation.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'What would be the effect of deleting the polyadenylation signal (AAUAAA) from an mRNA?', 'The mRNA would not be capped at the 5'' end', 'The mRNA would not be polyadenylated, leading to rapid degradation', 'Introns would not be spliced out', 'Translation would initiate at the wrong codon', 'B', 'The AAUAAA polyadenylation signal is required for cleavage and addition of the poly-A tail; without it, the mRNA is unstable and rapidly degraded, reducing protein output.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'Which type of RNA interference involves endogenous microRNAs that partially complement target mRNA sequences?', 'siRNA-mediated mRNA cleavage', 'miRNA-mediated translational repression', 'piRNA-mediated DNA methylation', 'lncRNA-mediated chromatin silencing', 'B', 'MicroRNAs (miRNAs) are endogenous ~22-nucleotide RNAs that typically bind imperfectly to the 3'' UTR of target mRNAs, recruiting RISC to repress translation or promote mRNA degradation.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'In the trp operon of E. coli, what happens when tryptophan is abundant?', 'Tryptophan binds the repressor and activates it, blocking the operator', 'Tryptophan degrades RNA polymerase', 'The trp operon is constitutively expressed', 'cAMP levels rise, activating the operon', 'A', 'The trp operon is a repressible operon; when tryptophan (the corepressor) is abundant, it binds to the inactive trp repressor, activating it so it can bind the operator and block transcription.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'A researcher uses a drug that inhibits histone deacetylases (HDACs). What effect would this have on transcription?', 'Transcription would decrease due to chromatin compaction', 'Transcription would increase because histone acetylation would accumulate, relaxing chromatin', 'RNA polymerase would be degraded', 'Introns would fail to be removed', 'B', 'HDACs remove acetyl groups from histones, condensing chromatin and repressing transcription. Inhibiting HDACs causes acetyl groups to accumulate, keeping chromatin open and promoting transcription.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'Which of the following describes the role of transcription factors in eukaryotic gene regulation?', 'They directly synthesize mRNA', 'They are proteins that bind specific DNA sequences and regulate transcription initiation', 'They are required only for translation, not transcription', 'They function the same as sigma factors in prokaryotes with no differences', 'B', 'Eukaryotic transcription factors are proteins that bind specific promoter or enhancer sequences and interact with RNA polymerase II or other components of the transcription machinery to activate or repress gene expression.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the end result of translation termination?', 'The ribosome duplicates', 'The polypeptide, mRNA, and ribosomal subunits are released', 'A new mRNA is produced', 'The polypeptide is inserted into the membrane', 'B', 'When a release factor binds the stop codon at the A site, it stimulates hydrolysis of the peptidyl-tRNA bond, releasing the polypeptide; the ribosome then dissociates into its subunits and releases the mRNA.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'molecular-biology', 'What is a plasmid and why is it used in genetic engineering?', 'A small circular RNA found in viruses', 'A small circular double-stranded DNA molecule in bacteria that replicates independently and can carry foreign genes', 'A type of transposable element', 'A fragment of chromosomal DNA used in PCR', 'B', 'Plasmids are small, circular, self-replicating DNA molecules in bacteria; they are used as vectors in cloning because foreign DNA can be inserted into them and they replicate inside host bacteria, amplifying the inserted gene.'),

-- hard molecular-biology
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'A researcher observes that a particular gene is expressed at high levels in liver cells but not in muscle cells, even though both cell types contain identical DNA. Which of the following best explains this tissue-specific expression?', 'The gene is amplified in liver cells but not in muscle cells', 'Different combinations of transcription factors and chromatin states in liver versus muscle cells differentially regulate gene expression', 'The gene is on a different chromosome in each cell type', 'Alternative splicing produces a liver-specific mRNA that is absent in muscle cells', 'B', 'Cell-type-specific gene expression is primarily controlled by differential transcription factor activity and epigenetic chromatin modifications; liver-specific activators and open chromatin at the gene''s regulatory regions drive expression in liver but not muscle.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'In an experiment, cells are treated with a drug that prevents topoisomerase from re-ligating DNA. What is the most likely consequence for replication?', 'Replication would be faster because supercoiling is eliminated', 'Replication forks would stall as torsional stress accumulates and DNA breaks cannot be repaired', 'Okazaki fragments would not be joined', 'RNA primers would accumulate', 'B', 'Topoisomerase must cut and re-ligate DNA to relieve supercoiling ahead of the replication fork. Preventing re-ligation causes persistent double-strand breaks, halts fork progression, and triggers DNA damage responses.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'An experimenter inserts a mutation that changes the -10 and -35 boxes of a prokaryotic promoter. Which outcome is most expected?', 'Increased binding of ribosomes to mRNA', 'Reduced binding of sigma factor and decreased transcription initiation', 'Faster elongation of the RNA transcript', 'Premature termination of transcription', 'B', 'The -10 and -35 boxes are consensus sequences recognized by the sigma factor of bacterial RNA polymerase; mutations here reduce sigma factor binding affinity and dramatically decrease or abolish transcription initiation.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'In X-chromosome inactivation, one X chromosome in female cells is silenced. Which epigenetic mechanisms are primarily responsible?', 'Histone acetylation and DNA demethylation', 'Coating of the inactive X by Xist lncRNA, histone H3K27 trimethylation, and DNA methylation', 'Deletion of genes on the inactive X', 'Overexpression of repressor proteins encoded on autosomes', 'B', 'X-inactivation involves Xist lncRNA coating the inactive X, recruiting Polycomb complexes that trimethylate H3K27 (a repressive mark), followed by DNA methylation of CpG islands, collectively silencing most genes on that chromosome.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'A gene encoding a transcription factor has a gain-of-function mutation making it constitutively active. If this transcription factor normally activates cell-cycle progression genes, what is the likely cellular outcome?', 'The cell enters permanent G0 arrest', 'Uncontrolled cell proliferation, potentially leading to cancer', 'Enhanced apoptosis', 'Reduced DNA replication fidelity', 'B', 'A constitutively active transcription factor that drives cell-cycle genes would continuously push the cell through the cell cycle, overcoming normal checkpoint controls and potentially causing oncogenic transformation.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'Researchers find that a protein requires both a DNA-binding domain and an activation domain to stimulate transcription. When they fuse the DNA-binding domain to a repressor activation domain, what happens?', 'Transcription increases because the protein binds DNA', 'Transcription of the target gene is repressed despite normal DNA binding', 'The protein cannot enter the nucleus', 'The promoter is methylated', 'B', 'Transcription factor function depends on the activation domain; replacing it with a repressor domain converts the factor into a repressor. The protein still binds its target sequence but now recruits repressor machinery, silencing the gene.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'Why do cells use both intrinsic and extrinsic pathways to initiate apoptosis, and how does p53 link DNA damage to this response?', 'p53 activates telomerase to extend chromosome ends when DNA is damaged', 'p53 is activated by DNA damage and transcriptionally upregulates pro-apoptotic genes like Bax, promoting mitochondrial cytochrome c release and caspase activation', 'p53 silences DNA repair genes, allowing damage to accumulate', 'The two apoptotic pathways are entirely independent of p53', 'B', 'Activated p53 (in response to DNA damage) induces transcription of pro-apoptotic Bcl-2 family members like Bax, which permeabilize the outer mitochondrial membrane, releasing cytochrome c, activating caspases, and committing the cell to apoptosis.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'In a Northern blot experiment comparing mRNA from two tissues, tissue A shows a larger mRNA band than tissue B for the same gene. What molecular event most likely explains this?', 'Tissue A has more ribosomes', 'Tissue A uses an alternative polyadenylation site or includes additional exons via alternative splicing, producing a longer mRNA', 'The gene has been duplicated in tissue A', 'Tissue A has lower mRNA degradation rates', 'B', 'Size differences in mRNA from the same gene between tissues are most commonly explained by alternative splicing (inclusion of additional exons) or use of alternative polyadenylation signals that produce longer 3'' UTRs, both resulting in longer mRNA isoforms.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'A cell has a mutation in the gene encoding a mismatch repair (MMR) protein. How does this increase cancer risk?', 'MMR proteins directly suppress oncogene transcription; their loss activates oncogenes', 'Without MMR, replication errors (mismatched bases) go uncorrected, increasing mutation rate across the genome and elevating the chance of hitting tumor suppressor or oncogene loci', 'MMR proteins degrade reactive oxygen species; their loss causes oxidative DNA damage', 'The mutation prevents cell division entirely', 'B', 'Mismatch repair corrects base-base mismatches introduced by replication errors. Loss of MMR causes microsatellite instability and a genome-wide increase in point mutations, raising the probability of accumulating mutations in cancer-relevant genes.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the molecular mechanism by which telomeres shorten with each cell division, and how does telomerase prevent this?', 'Telomeres are degraded by exonucleases; telomerase inhibits these enzymes', 'DNA polymerase cannot fully replicate the 5'' end of a linear chromosome after primer removal, shortening telomeres; telomerase adds repetitive sequences using its own RNA template', 'Each replication removes one nucleosome from the telomere; telomerase repackages nucleosomes', 'Telomeres are damaged by reactive oxygen species; telomerase repairs this oxidative damage', 'B', 'The "end-replication problem" arises because removal of the RNA primer at the 5'' end leaves a gap that cannot be filled, shortening the chromosome. Telomerase is a reverse transcriptase with an RNA template that adds TTAGGG repeats to chromosome ends, compensating for this loss.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'A researcher knocks out the gene for Dicer in mouse embryonic stem cells. What would be the most direct molecular consequence?', 'DNA replication would fail', 'Pre-miRNAs could not be processed into mature miRNAs, disrupting post-transcriptional gene regulation', 'Splicing of all pre-mRNAs would be blocked', 'Histone methylation would increase globally', 'B', 'Dicer is the endonuclease that cleaves pre-miRNA hairpins into mature miRNA duplexes. Without Dicer, the biogenesis of miRNAs and siRNAs is blocked, eliminating RNA interference-mediated post-transcriptional regulation.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'How does attenuation regulate the trp operon in addition to the repressor-operator mechanism?', 'Attenuation uses a small molecule to block the TATA box', 'When tryptophan is abundant, the ribosome translates the leader peptide rapidly, causing the mRNA to form a terminator hairpin that halts transcription before the structural genes', 'Attenuation methylates the trp operon promoter when tryptophan is scarce', 'Attenuation involves siRNA degradation of trp mRNA', 'B', 'Attenuation is a translation-transcription coupling mechanism: with abundant Trp, charged Trp-tRNA allows fast translation of the leader peptide, favoring a terminator hairpin in the mRNA that prematurely terminates transcription of the trp biosynthesis genes.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'In two-hybrid yeast experiments, how is a protein-protein interaction detected?', 'By measuring the size of proteins on a gel', 'By reconstituting a transcription factor: one fusion protein carries a DNA-binding domain, the other carries an activation domain; interaction brings both domains together to activate a reporter gene', 'By immunoprecipitation of tagged proteins', 'By FRET between fluorescently labeled proteins', 'B', 'The yeast two-hybrid system uses split transcription factors: bait fused to a DNA-binding domain and prey fused to an activation domain. Only when bait and prey interact is the transcription factor reconstituted, activating a reporter like lacZ or HIS3.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the molecular basis for dominance of oncogenic Ras mutations over wild-type Ras alleles in cancer?', 'The mutant Ras protein degrades the wild-type protein', 'Mutant Ras is locked in the GTP-bound active state because it has impaired GTPase activity, continuously signaling even when one wild-type allele is present', 'The mutant Ras gene is overexpressed due to promoter amplification', 'The mutant Ras protein activates tumor suppressors', 'B', 'Oncogenic Ras mutations (commonly at Gly12) impair its intrinsic GTPase activity and resistance to GAP-stimulated hydrolysis, trapping Ras-GTP in the active state. This gain-of-function dominance means even one mutant allele continuously activates downstream proliferation pathways.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'A genome-wide ChIP-seq experiment uses an antibody against H3K4me3. What type of genomic regions would be most enriched in the results?', 'Heterochromatic regions and silenced genes', 'Active gene promoters and transcription start sites', 'Origins of replication', 'Centromeric repeat sequences', 'B', 'H3K4me3 (trimethylation of histone H3 lysine 4) is a histone mark strongly associated with active gene promoters and transcription start sites; ChIP-seq would therefore enrich for these regulatory regions.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'During DNA repair via nucleotide excision repair (NER), what is the correct sequence of events?', 'Ligation → incision → excision → resynthesis', 'Recognition of lesion → dual incision → excision of oligonucleotide → DNA synthesis to fill gap → ligation', 'Base removal → strand incision → ligation', 'Strand invasion → Holliday junction formation → branch migration', 'B', 'NER removes bulky DNA lesions (e.g., thymine dimers): damage is recognized, the DNA is unwound, dual incisions are made flanking the lesion, the ~25–32 nt oligonucleotide is removed, DNA polymerase fills the gap, and ligase seals the nick.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'Explain why loss of heterozygosity (LOH) at a tumor suppressor locus accelerates tumor development.', 'LOH increases the number of copies of the tumor suppressor, producing too much protein', 'When the remaining wild-type allele of a tumor suppressor is lost (second hit), the cell completely lacks the braking function, allowing uncontrolled growth per Knudson''s two-hit model', 'LOH causes the tumor suppressor protein to become constitutively active', 'LOH is irrelevant to cancer because a single wild-type allele is always sufficient', 'B', 'Knudson''s two-hit hypothesis states tumor suppressor genes require inactivation of both alleles. LOH eliminates the remaining wild-type allele (through deletion, recombination, or mutation), removing all tumor suppressor function and releasing the brake on cell proliferation.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'A researcher designs an antisense oligonucleotide complementary to the 5'' UTR of an mRNA. What is the likely molecular outcome?', 'The oligonucleotide acts as a primer for DNA synthesis', 'The oligonucleotide blocks ribosome scanning, preventing translation initiation', 'The oligonucleotide activates the mRNA for splicing', 'The oligonucleotide methylates the mRNA cap', 'B', 'Antisense oligonucleotides base-pair with their target mRNA; when targeting the 5'' UTR, they physically block the scanning 43S pre-initiation complex from reaching the start codon, preventing translation without necessarily degrading the mRNA.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the molecular explanation for why cancer cells with high telomerase activity are considered more malignant?', 'Telomerase degrades p53, removing apoptotic checkpoints', 'Telomerase prevents telomere shortening, allowing cancer cells to replicate indefinitely rather than entering senescence or crisis', 'Telomerase methylates DNA, silencing immune evasion genes', 'High telomerase activity increases mutation rate directly', 'B', 'Somatic cells progressively shorten telomeres with each division, eventually triggering senescence or crisis. Cancer cells that re-express telomerase maintain telomere length, bypassing this proliferative limit and achieving cellular immortality.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'How does homologous recombination repair a double-strand break (DSB), and why is it generally more accurate than NHEJ?', 'HR uses the broken ends directly without a template; NHEJ uses a homologous chromosome', 'HR uses a homologous sister chromatid as a precise template, accurately restoring the sequence; NHEJ re-ligates broken ends without a template, often introducing small insertions or deletions', 'Both mechanisms are equally accurate but operate at different cell cycle stages', 'NHEJ is more accurate because it uses multiple proofreading steps', 'B', 'Homologous recombination (HR) searches for a homologous template (usually the sister chromatid) and uses it to guide accurate repair. NHEJ simply ligates the broken ends, frequently introducing indels, making it error-prone but fast.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'In an in vitro transcription experiment, adding a competitor DNA with the same promoter sequence reduces mRNA output. This suggests which mechanism?', 'The competitor DNA sequesters RNA polymerase and transcription factors away from the target promoter', 'The competitor DNA degrades the mRNA product', 'The competitor DNA inhibits ribosome function', 'The competitor DNA activates a transcriptional repressor', 'A', 'Adding excess competitor DNA with the same promoter titrates (sequesters) the limiting transcription factors and RNA polymerase, reducing their availability for the target promoter and thereby decreasing its transcriptional output.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'A newly synthesized polypeptide destined for the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) has a signal sequence at its N-terminus. What is the molecular mechanism by which this signal directs the protein?', 'The signal sequence binds cytoplasmic chaperones that carry the protein to the mitochondria', 'The signal sequence is recognized by the signal recognition particle (SRP), which pauses translation and docks the ribosome at the ER membrane for co-translational translocation', 'The signal sequence is cleaved in the cytoplasm before the protein folds', 'The signal sequence binds ribosomes to the nucleus', 'B', 'The hydrophobic signal sequence emerging from the ribosome is recognized by SRP, which arrests translation and escorts the ribosome-mRNA-nascent polypeptide complex to the SRP receptor on the ER membrane, where translation resumes and the polypeptide is threaded co-translationally into the ER lumen.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'How does phosphorylation of the RNA polymerase II CTD (C-terminal domain) regulate the transition from transcription initiation to elongation?', 'Phosphorylation causes RNA polymerase to dissociate from the template completely', 'Phosphorylation of Ser5 of the CTD heptad repeats by TFIIH releases RNA polymerase from the promoter-bound complex (promoter clearance) and initiates capping enzyme recruitment', 'CTD phosphorylation recruits the large ribosomal subunit', 'Dephosphorylated CTD is required for elongation', 'B', 'TFIIH phosphorylates Ser5 of the heptapeptide repeats in the RNA pol II CTD, triggering promoter clearance and transitioning the polymerase into an elongation-competent form; the phospho-CTD also serves as a platform for recruiting 5'' capping enzymes.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the evidence that RNA was likely the first informational molecule (the "RNA world" hypothesis)?', 'RNA is more stable than DNA under all conditions', 'Ribozymes can both store information and catalyze reactions, RNA is central to all modern translation machinery, and RNA precedes DNA in biosynthetic pathways', 'RNA can replicate without any enzymes in all laboratory conditions today', 'DNA evolved before RNA based on fossil record evidence', 'B', 'The RNA world hypothesis is supported by: ribozymes (catalytic RNAs like the ribosome''s peptidyl transferase center, self-splicing introns), RNA''s dual capacity to store information and catalyze reactions, and the fact that deoxyribonucleotides are made by reducing ribonucleotides, suggesting RNA chemistry came first.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'A researcher uses chromatin immunoprecipitation (ChIP) followed by sequencing. What does this technique reveal?', 'The sequence of all mRNA molecules in a cell', 'Genome-wide binding sites of a protein of interest in vivo', 'The three-dimensional folding of chromosomes', 'Post-translational modifications of secreted proteins', 'B', 'ChIP-seq cross-links proteins to DNA in living cells, then immunoprecipitates a protein of interest along with associated DNA, which is sequenced to identify all genomic loci where that protein (e.g., a transcription factor or modified histone) is bound genome-wide.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'In bacteria, how does Rho-dependent transcription termination work?', 'A hairpin forms in the mRNA that causes RNA polymerase to pause and dissociate', 'The Rho helicase tracks along the mRNA and uses ATP to unwind the mRNA-DNA hybrid at a paused polymerase, releasing the transcript', 'A sigma factor recognizes a termination signal and releases the transcript', 'Rho methylates the 3'' end of the RNA, signaling termination', 'B', 'In Rho-dependent termination, the Rho protein (an ATP-dependent RNA helicase) binds a rut (Rho utilization) site in the nascent mRNA and translocates 5'' to 3'', catching up to a paused RNA polymerase and using its helicase activity to unwind the RNA-DNA hybrid, releasing the transcript.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the molecular basis for antibiotic resistance conferred by beta-lactamases?', 'Beta-lactamases modify the ribosomal target of beta-lactam antibiotics', 'Beta-lactamases hydrolyze the beta-lactam ring of antibiotics like penicillin, inactivating them before they can inhibit bacterial cell wall synthesis', 'Beta-lactamases pump antibiotics out of the cell via efflux pumps', 'Beta-lactamases methylate the antibiotic, preventing it from entering the cell', 'B', 'Beta-lactamases catalyze hydrolysis of the beta-lactam ring (the pharmacophore of penicillins and cephalosporins), destroying antibiotic activity before it can inhibit transpeptidases involved in peptidoglycan synthesis.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'A synthetic biology experiment creates a minimal cell with only 473 genes. Which of the following categories of genes would be absolutely essential?', 'Only metabolic genes for energy production', 'Genes for DNA replication, transcription, translation, and cell membrane integrity', 'Only genes encoding structural proteins', 'Genes for complex behaviors like chemotaxis', 'B', 'A minimal cell must maintain the core molecular biology processes: replicating its genome, transcribing genes, translating proteins, and maintaining a membrane boundary — all other complex behaviors can be dispensed with.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'Describe how the SOS response in bacteria illustrates gene regulation under DNA damage conditions.', 'The SOS response constitutively expresses all DNA repair genes at all times', 'Under normal conditions, LexA represses SOS genes; DNA damage generates ssDNA that activates RecA, which stimulates LexA self-cleavage, derepressing dozens of DNA repair and tolerance genes', 'DNA damage in bacteria activates p53, which upregulates the SOS genes', 'The SOS response involves phosphorylation of RNA polymerase, redirecting it to repair genes', 'B', 'The SOS response: ssDNA produced at stalled replication forks binds RecA, forming a nucleoprotein filament with protease activity. Activated RecA stimulates auto-cleavage of the LexA repressor, derepressing ~40 SOS genes involved in DNA repair (e.g., uvrA, recA, umuC) and error-prone polymerases.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'Why does the fidelity of translation (~1 error per 10,000 amino acids) matter for protein function, and what mechanisms achieve this accuracy?', 'High error rates improve protein diversity; there are no mechanisms to improve accuracy', 'Errors produce misfolded proteins that waste energy; accuracy is achieved by codon-anticodon base pairing, ribosomal proofreading in the A site, and aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase editing activities', 'Translation accuracy is entirely determined by tRNA concentration', 'The ribosome uses ATP hydrolysis to proofread every amino acid added', 'B', 'Misincorporation generates aberrant proteins that may misfold, aggregate, or have toxic gain-of-function. Accuracy is achieved at multiple levels: aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases have editing sites to correct mischarged tRNAs, ribosomal decoding delays GTP hydrolysis (kinetic proofreading) until correct anticodon-codon pairing is confirmed.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'How does the pioneer transcription factor FOXA1 access nucleosomal DNA to initiate cell-type-specific gene expression?', 'FOXA1 recruits histone acetyltransferases that first must open all nucleosomes genome-wide', 'FOXA1 has a winged-helix domain that mimics linker histone binding, allowing it to bind nucleosome-wrapped DNA and recruit remodeling complexes to open chromatin at specific loci', 'FOXA1 degrades histones at its target loci', 'FOXA1 enters only after another activator first opens the chromatin', 'B', 'Pioneer factors like FOXA1 can bind their motifs even in compacted chromatin because their DNA-binding domain structurally mimics linker histones and can interact with the nucleosome core. After binding, FOXA1 recruits chromatin remodeling and histone-modifying complexes to open the locus for subsequent transcription factor binding.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'In cancer, CpG island methylation of tumor suppressor gene promoters is common. What molecular mechanism links this methylation to transcriptional silencing?', 'Methylated cytosines attract RNA polymerase, over-activating the gene', 'Methylated CpGs are bound by methyl-CpG-binding proteins (e.g., MeCP2) that recruit histone deacetylases and chromatin compaction complexes, silencing transcription', 'The methylation physically prevents RNA polymerase from binding the template strand', 'Methylation converts cytosine to uracil, creating nonsense mutations', 'B', 'Methyl-CpG-binding domain proteins (like MeCP2) specifically recognize 5-methylcytosine at CpG dinucleotides and recruit co-repressor complexes containing HDACs, which deacetylate histones and condense chromatin, silencing the associated promoter.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'An RNA aptamer is selected that binds a small molecule and, when placed in the 5'' UTR of an mRNA, inhibits translation upon ligand binding. This design is called a riboswitch. How does it function mechanistically?', 'The small molecule activates RNase to degrade the mRNA', 'Ligand binding changes the aptamer''s secondary structure, sequestering the ribosome binding site in a stem-loop that blocks ribosome access', 'The small molecule methylates the ribosome, preventing translation', 'The aptamer recruits siRNA complementary to the coding sequence', 'B', 'Riboswitches are RNA regulatory elements in which ligand binding induces a conformational change; in a translational riboswitch, ligand binding causes the aptamer domain to fold in a way that sequesters the Shine-Dalgarno sequence or AUG start codon in an inaccessible stem-loop structure, blocking ribosome binding.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the molecular consequence of a protein having both a nuclear localization signal (NLS) and a nuclear export signal (NES), and how does regulated masking of these signals control subcellular localization?', 'The protein is permanently retained in the nucleus because NLS is stronger', 'The balance between active import and export can be regulated post-translationally; phosphorylation or protein binding can mask either signal, allowing the cell to control where the protein resides in response to signals', 'The NLS and NES cancel out, keeping the protein in the cytoplasm', 'Such proteins are degraded immediately in the nucleus', 'B', 'Proteins with both NLS and NES shuttle between nucleus and cytoplasm; regulatory events like phosphorylation or binding to inhibitor proteins can selectively expose or mask each signal, thereby controlling nuclear-cytoplasmic distribution dynamically in response to cellular signals.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'How does nonsense-mediated decay (NMD) identify and degrade aberrant mRNAs?', 'NMD degrades all mRNAs lacking a poly-A tail', 'NMD recognizes mRNAs with a premature stop codon followed by an exon junction complex (EJC) downstream, triggering UPF1 helicase recruitment and mRNA degradation', 'NMD uses Dicer to cleave mRNAs containing stop codons', 'NMD phosphorylates ribosomes stalled at premature stop codons', 'B', 'NMD is a surveillance pathway that detects premature termination codons (PTCs): when a ribosome terminates at a stop codon more than ~50–55 nucleotides upstream of an EJC (left by splicing), UPF1 is recruited and activated, leading to mRNA decapping and degradation.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'A mutation in the splice donor site (GU at the 5'' end of an intron) of a gene is found in a patient with a genetic disease. Explain the molecular consequence and a possible phenotypic outcome.', 'The mutation silently changes the intron sequence with no effect', 'The spliceosome cannot recognize the mutant splice donor; the intron is retained in the mRNA, extending the open reading frame or introducing a premature stop, producing a truncated or aberrant protein', 'The mutation causes the intron to be spliced out twice', 'The mutation activates a cryptic promoter', 'B', 'The GU dinucleotide at the 5'' splice site is essential for U1 snRNA base pairing during spliceosome assembly. Mutation here prevents U1 binding, blocking normal splicing; the intron is retained, usually disrupting the reading frame or introducing a premature stop codon, resulting in a nonfunctional protein and disease phenotype.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'How do super-enhancers differ from typical enhancers in driving oncogene expression in cancer cells?', 'Super-enhancers are located within the coding sequence of oncogenes', 'Super-enhancers are very large clusters of enhancers with unusually high concentrations of transcriptional coactivators (e.g., BRD4, Mediator, H3K27ac) that drive very high expression of nearby oncogenes', 'Super-enhancers function identically to typical enhancers but are physically closer to the promoter', 'Super-enhancers encode regulatory noncoding RNAs that replace transcription factors', 'B', 'Super-enhancers are large domains (up to 50 kb) defined by exceptionally high levels of H3K27ac, BRD4, Mediator, and p300; they are disproportionately associated with cell-identity genes and oncogenes in cancer, where they are often formed or amplified de novo to drive very high transcription.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'In bacteria, how does the stringent response coordinate global gene regulation in response to amino acid starvation?', 'Uncharged tRNA in the ribosomal A site activates RelA to synthesize ppGpp, which inhibits rRNA transcription and redirects resources to amino acid biosynthesis', 'Amino acid starvation directly degrades sigma factor, stopping all transcription', 'The stringent response activates ribosome biogenesis to make more ribosomes', 'ppGpp activates translation of all mRNAs equally to compensate for amino acid depletion', 'A', 'During amino acid starvation, uncharged tRNA accumulates in the ribosomal A site, activating the ribosome-associated synthetase RelA to produce the alarmone ppGpp (guanosine tetraphosphate). ppGpp binds RNA polymerase and DksA to inhibit rRNA and ribosome biosynthesis genes while activating amino acid biosynthesis and stress-response genes.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'molecular-biology', 'What is the mechanism by which PCNA functions as a sliding clamp during DNA replication, and why is this important for processivity?', 'PCNA is a primase that synthesizes RNA primers; it increases processivity by adding multiple primers', 'PCNA forms a ring-shaped homotrimer loaded around double-stranded DNA by the clamp loader RFC; it tethers DNA polymerase delta to the template, preventing dissociation and enabling highly processive synthesis of thousands of nucleotides per binding event', 'PCNA is a helicase that moves ahead of the polymerase to unwind DNA more rapidly', 'PCNA methylates newly replicated DNA to prevent re-replication', 'B', 'PCNA (proliferating cell nuclear antigen) is a trimeric ring that encircles dsDNA and is loaded by RFC. It acts as a processivity clamp by physically tethering DNA polymerase to the template, allowing the polymerase to synthesize long stretches without falling off, achieving the high processivity needed for chromosomal replication.');
